","1230":"1230","1273":"1273","1150":"1150","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, England":"Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","London, England, United Kingdom":"London, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Melton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from any of various places, for example in Leicestershire, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, and Yorkshire, all of which have the same origin as   Middleton  , with Old English <i>middel</i> replaced by its Old Norse equivalent <i>methal</i> after the Scandinavian settlement of northern and eastern England."],"variants":[{"name":"Middleton","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places so called. In over thirty instances from many different areas, the name is from Old English <i>midel</i> ‘middle’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. However, Middleton on the Hill near Leominster in Herefordshire appears in Domesday Book as <i>Miceltune</i>, the first element clearly being Old English <i>micel</i> ‘large’, ‘great’ (see   Middlebrook  ). Middleton Baggot and Middleton Priors in Shropshire have early spellings that suggest <i>gem̄thhyll</i> (from <i>gem̄th</i> ‘confluence’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’) + <i>tūn</i> as the origin. This surname is also found in Scotland and Ireland.","History: A Scottish family of this name derives it from lands at Middleto(u)n near Kincardine. The Scottish physician Peter Middleton practiced in New York City after 1752 and was one of the founders of the medical school at King's College (now Columbia University) in 1767. One of the earliest of the Charleston, SC, Middleton family of prominent legislators was Arthur Middleton, born in Charleston in 1681. The name has also been established in Ireland since at least the 13th century; its presence was reinforced by settlers in the 17th century."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Melton was born in 1200, in London, England, United Kingdom as the son of Siward de Meltone and Mrs Siward de Metone. He married Mrs. John Melton in 1225, in London, Middlesex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1200–":"1200–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1215–1273":"1215–1273","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1228–Female":"1228–Surnud","1150–1230":"1150–1230","–Female":"Surnud","1228":"1228","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","before 1200":"enne 1200","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1273":"1273","1150":"1150","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, England":"Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","London, England, United Kingdom":"London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1200–":"1200–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1215–1273":"1215–1273","1205–Female":"1205–Kuollut","1228–Female":"1228–Kuollut","1150–1230":"1150–1230","–Female":"Kuollut","1228":"1228","1205":"1205","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","before 1200":"ennen vuotta 1200","1200":"1200","1230":"1230","1273":"1273","1150":"1150","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, England":"Milton Keynes, Buckinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"England","London, England, United Kingdom":"London, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1200–":"1200–Décédé","1200–Male":"1200–Décédé","1215–1273":"1215–1273","1205–Female":"1205–Décédée","1228–Female":"1228–Décédée","1150–1230":"